I had a major breakthrough this practice. I started practicing yoga regularly a couple months ago, and the mindfulness aspect of yoga has been both beneficial and really frustrating. My mind always wanders. I try to quietly note the thoughts I'm having, but then I start thinking about why I'm having those thoughts in the first place, and then I note those thoughts, and so on and so forth until I'm thoroughly  out of the moment and shaming myself. But this practice, I had a breakthrough. It really resonated when you used the metaphor of welcoming your thoughts like welcoming guests to a party. You notice their knocking, open the door, and briefly greet them before letting them inside. Then they step away to go mingle with the other thoughts/guests to create a special and unique moment in your body, in your home. As the host, you just welcome them with warmth and kindness, until at some point, they leave.
Thanks Adriene , I absolutely love your yoga classes. I have come back to the mat and really feel good. So thanks and have a merry Christmas from New Zealand.

I am a teenager with a chronic illness that makes it almost impossible for me to do normal daily activities non the less exercise, but I really wanted to try and do some form of physical movement. So even though I can't hold all of the positions the entire time and even though I have to take lots of breaks I want to encourage anyone else struggling through the practice to remember that you are here. You made a choice to better yourself even though it is hard and painful. It's okay if you have to adapt the pose's to work for your body, just to sit on your mat and breath is progress. So just close your eyes and take a breath and remember that you can do this!

I am a woodworker. I have always found that I almost never finish my projects, the fun ones that I do just for me. This week it has become clear to me just how impatient I am, how I am always rushing to try and finish a project or start the next one. I am forcing myself each morning to practice patience with this 30 day yoga practice. 30-45 minutes seems like a lot of time to spend on "stretching" or at least thats how i used to look at it. Just spending this time each morning and forcing myself to slow down has really helped me calm my busy brain and it's goodness is spreading to all aspects of my life. thank you

Thank you Adriene for this beautiful yoga journey and for your words today. You said: "listening to your body doing this type of work that is not fast." This really resonated with me today. I am an artist, performer and theatre maker, and I notice how much I feel the pressure to create, make and churn out work. I would love to be more patient in creating and to keep remembering this virtue of patience and slowness. To make work in processes that are more deep, slow and precise and to stand by that despite the many pulls. I thought today in this session: I'd love my theatre practice to look more like yoga! There is a sense of gentle discipline...the work is being done but in a slow way. Thank you. I wish you a lot of love and light. May you receive a lot of all the abundance you share here. Love XXX

I restarted this 30 day journey over I skipped some days, skipped some videos, and half-assed other videos. I got to the point where it felt like I lost connection to my commitment to daily practice. I put a sticker in my planner every day that I do yoga but despite doing yoga almost every day in January, I wasn't proud when I saw my planner because I knew I hadn't kept the promise to myself I had wanted to. I want to do this with full commitment. The old Jade would beat herself up over making mistakes the first time and then she would never try again. I've been doing yoga with Adriene for a couple years now and I've learned that yoga never wants you to beat yourself up. All yoga requires of you is that you get on the mat again. It doesn't care how long it's been or where your skill level is. all it cares is that you are there today. Now on Day 4, I feel more connected to this practice and myself than I ever felt before. Thank you for everything you've given me Adriene. You are my rock. Your videos help me find my connection to myself, to my gratitude, to my community, to my body, and most importantly, to my breath.

I'm a few days behind (finished day 4 on 1/9, will do day 5 today) and I'm ok with that.  I have an intensely stressful job which I've been doing from home since March, and I have struggled with boundaries by having my work space in my home space. I started on Monday, 1/4 (I skipped Wednesday - was too much happening, which was a bit paralyzing, but got back to it Thursday).  Rather than doing this in the mornings (when I meditate and have dedicated time with no meetings to catch up on emails and correspondence), I have been doing this program as soon as my last meeting of the day ends (before I get sucked into lots more follow-up, emailing, etc., for many hours into the evening).  It has been the perfect way to create a boundary between work and "my" time in the evening.  While I'm getting the heart rate up a wee bit for some good health benefits, it's also slowing it, and my MIND, down, to focus on me.  Going from the practice to the kitchen to prepare a healthy dinner has become quite enjoyable.  Thank you, Adriene, for this marvelous program and your phenomenal positive energy.  (Now, if I could just get Wanda to relax on the sidelines like Benji, that would be great too... alas, she's a cat, who wants to be on me most of the time...)

I hurt myself, I don't know.. a month or two ago. I was pushing on something at work and suddenly between my shoulder blades, right dead center of my spine tensed up like I've never felt before. The deep pain persisted for about a week. I couldn't sit or rest in certain positions without being in agony. Breathing hurt. Though it's gotten better, there are times during my practice that I feel it again. I'm careful not to push too far or too hard. Just trying to wake it up kinda and put some mobility back in it really. At this point I'm not ashamed to admit I'm making modifications to accommodate this section of my spine but in years past I would have pushed through or been embarrassed to admit it, if even to myself.

I really am my best teacher and thanks, Adriene, for reminding me of that today. I'm going to continue to work towards doing what I can and whether or not my pain ever goes away, I don't think I'll forget the lesson.

Expectantly I arrived at the mat to find and listen to the heartbeat. I slowly stepped into the ocean breath and kept listening for the call to synchronize, I could not hear it. My thoughts were fixed even a bit consuming trying to control that which was not there. Ujjayi, ocean breath, breath of life engulfed the mind and grounded me to enjoy the movement and deepened the inhaled and extend the exhale to be present and arrive aware after each transition. Finally, when in was able to let go, I hear it, the warm rhythm of the heartbeat and I choose to stay there and extend the experience practicing Release. 
Each day of this series afirma and confirms that my journey is about being present, listening, seeing, feeling. It is about the here and now, that‚Äôs real, that‚Äôs the joy.

Today was a tough day as we started on the back. My back froze with a shooting pain and I felt anxious about it from the minute you said, let‚Äôs lie back in a flatback position. When you started the bridge pose, my body shuddered due to the pain but I tried to force myself to do it which caused more pain. I almost felt like leaving but I focused on slowing down my breath and took 7 minutes to peel myself back to a sitting posture and acknowledging the pain I felt. I stayed, your voice playing while I went to an extended child's pose which is my own resting pose. While you guided through slow bridges, I breathed deep and slow in my extended child‚Äôs pose until I was calmer again. Then I restarted the video, this time by surrendering completely and embracing myself for any pain I felt. And the back pain was gone! I was able to do all the bridges and finished the entire practice. Days like today reinforce the feeling that hardest part is showing up and staying. And I am glad that I stayed and tuned into my breath to bring me back. Thank you for giving the mantra- ‚Äúmy breath is my anchor, my anchor is my breath‚Äù. I understand it now. <3

my personal adjustments for knee pain (if you cannot put pressure on the knee):
12:22 - grab your thigh and not the lower leg to pull towards your body; use your hands as a little cussion between thigh and lower leg to avoid a too deep stretch in the knee
18:20 - sit cross-legged and simply do the cat-cow by moving your upper body front and back/ spinal flex
18:58 - just lift the leg (and welcome the heat), transition to/from this pose from standing
21:24 - use a table

It's inevitable though each 30 day series that some days are harder than others. Some days, I have a difficult time sitting with myself and just being. Today was one of those days. I had a hard time dropping into this slow pace and I was finding myself dealing with feelings of frustration. But yaknow what? That's totally ok! The birthday messages and call from family and friends, my son‚Äôs wobbly baby steps, the snow falling from the giant oak tree in our yard(I observed this during the practice today) all have deeper meaning to me today. Deciding to join this yoga practice was the best gift I could give myself.  I‚Äôve tried it in the past and it always felt like a chore and I never kept it up. Day 4: yes! still going!

This morning was fun because I came to practice right out of bed, so it was as much a wake-up as an exercise routine.  This one was a lot slower, which I think worked pretty well for that; we'll see if I can make it this early on other days, and how they go in return.

More work on using the ujaii breath to keep focused even when my brain is running off to other things.  And yes, I did have to pause during the opening listening on our back to quiet my head down for a while, before I could pull it back in.  And that was okay, and allowed, and when I did it I felt better and was able to focus better, so it was worth it.

I really appreciate the days we're on our hands a little less.  My wrists get so much use with typing and knitting so much all the time, and I'm working on strengthening them, but they HURT sometimes, and there's not a lot of good modifications for easing up on them a little.  This was nice.
